## Part 4 — IAM (Least Privilege, Multi-Region)

The region is **part of the ARN**, so each instance gets its own ARN with its own region.

Lambda → **Configuration → Permissions → Role name → Add Permissions → Create Inline Policy → JSON:**

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "ControlOnlyMyInstances",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "ec2:StartInstances",
        "ec2:StopInstances",
        "ec2:RebootInstances"
      ],
      "Resource": [
        "arn:aws:ec2:ap-south-1:YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID:instance/i-0aaa1111111111111",
        "arn:aws:ec2:us-east-1:YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID:instance/i-0bbb2222222222222",
        "arn:aws:ec2:eu-west-1:YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID:instance/i-0ccc3333333333333"
      ]
    },
    {
      "Sid": "DescribeNeedsWildcard",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": ["ec2:DescribeInstances"],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
```

Name it `EC2DiscordControlMultiRegion` → **Create**.

> 🔒 **Why two statements?** `DescribeInstances` does **not** support resource-level ARNs (AWS limitation), but Start/Stop/Reboot do. Even if the bot is compromised, it can only touch the exact instances **you listed** — in the exact regions you listed — not your whole account.

> 📝 When you add a new instance or region later, add its ARN here too.

